The Dome of the Rock that now occupies the location was built by Muslims in its initial form in AD 691–692, collapsed in 1015, and was rebuilt in 1022–23. Jews and Christians are not now permitted to enter the Dome. Prior to that restriction, my wife and I entered the Dome about 20 years ago, a fascinating story may have to tell sometime.  Most of our first tour group then went with us to Jordan, October 3-5, to explore ancient Petra and to “camp” in air conditioned huts in the dessert of Wadi Rum. They all then depart departed to their various home destinations as our second group began arriving, 59 for our second tour of Jordan, preparatory to then making our journey to Israel to meet up with the rest of our second tour group.  Early Sabbath morning, October 7, we visited Mount Nebo, where Moses was laid to rest by God after looking out over the Promised Land he would never enter, only to then be resurrected and taken to the heavenly Canaan after a battle ensued over his body between Satan and the pre-incarnate Christ (Jude 1:9).  David and I both heard explosions in the distance while we stood with our group on Mount Nebo.  We then went on to worship and preach at the Madaba Adventist Church, while all hell was breaking loose in Israel that very morning. On Sunday we made our way again to Petra and Wadi Rum with our second group. As the news began slowly trickling to us, some of our second Israel group began arriving into Tel Aviv to meet up with us, even as Hamas began targeting the airport with missile launches. Others who were scheduled to arrive over the next two days began cancelling their flights as news of the war was breaking worldwide. Family and friends began texting us with details of the escalating war and urging us to “get out.” My daughter Amber, who was with us for the first tour and had departed, texted me, “You need t come home.” As we went to sleep in the Wadi Rum desert October 8 and woke up early the next morning, it became crystal clear that we needed to immediately mobilize to get our people out of the region safely. We made the sad announcement that the remainder of our tour must be canceled and gave everyone a deadline of two hours to make use of the Internet connection we had at Wadi Rum to make arrangements for exit flights ASAP. Standing and sitting outside on desert sands in the early morning air, everyone manifesting a beautiful Christian spirit, we all scrambled to get new flights. As the two-hour window closed, the last couple successfully booked their flights and jumped onboard. Amazed and grateful for how quickly it all came together, two tour buses full of Christian pilgrims made our five-hour drive to Amman, Jordan, from which our flight would depart.  Driving along, our Muslim Jordanian tour guide spoke with a painful glassiness in his eyes, “I am in my 60s. People sometimes ask me, ‘Are you happy here?’ His voice full of sadness, he said, ‘Happy? What is happy? This cycle of violence is all I've known my whole life. It never stops, and with each new cycle of violence it gets worse and more bloody. My children and grandchildren witness one hateful battle after another. On both sides, our children are raised to believe lies about one another and to hate one another. The children that are now growing up will be the next ones to wage war against one another. Why? Why do we hate each other? Why can we not have peace?”  Why, indeed!  As we arrived at our destination and got off the buses, we told him we loved him and he said he loved us too. I believe him.  David notified me that he was able to get a flight out late last night. My flight departs, God willing, at 1am October 11, twelve hours from now. I so desperately want to go home, and and even more desperately want all of us to go HOME. I sit here waiting for my flight with the ancient Hebrew prayer on my lips:  Fearfulness and trembling have come upon me, And horror has overwhelmed me. So I said, “Oh, that I had wings like a dove! I would fly away and be at rest” (Psalm 55:5-6).", 'user': {'name': 'Ty Gibson', 'username': '@tyfgibson', 'profile_id': '1490171355253424128', 'avatar': 'https://pbs.twimg.com/profile_images/1490171355253424128/-CKUN4Da_mini.jpg'}, 'date': 'Oct 10, 2023 · 11:03 AM UTC', 'pictures': [], 'videos': [], 'gifs': []}

Erin O\'Toole the pro-lockdown leader of the conservative party was likewise forced to resign, his temporary replacement Candice Bergen (not to be mistaken with the actress) being a longtime rival opposed to lockdowns, and his main rival who replaced her after party elections were  @PierrePoilievre  , the Politician after  @MaximeBernier    who was quickest to embrace the Truckers and their cry for freedom. Naturally, the go-to use of the Senate is as a spoils system for cronies. Do some shameful favour for a prime minister, raise a lot of money for the party, and be politically connected to a provincial gov the PM wants to buy off... Get a Senate seat.  One of the longest-standing political agreements in Canada is how badly the Senate needs to be abolished... but can\'t be because Quebec is nominally overrepresented in the Senate, and abolishing it would cause a constitutional crisis.  So mostly the Senate keeps its head down and tries to avoid the news... because it will never be sympathetic. That body was called upon to sign off on the Emergencies Act...  And all these self-important losers smelled blood in the water.   .  Did they have some principled stand on civil liberties grounds? With mere hours left to the deadline and no passage in sight... Trudeau voluntarily withdrew the act.   . Instead, Trudeau weekly tried to claim victory... There were no protestors in Ottawa or on bridges! But in the week that followed lockdown measures were quickly and quietly pulled back. Alberta had already rescinded their measures, and other provinces were following suit. text: BREAKING: Vladimir Putin considering the establishment of a Palestinian state as “necessary” appears to be aligned with Russia’s longstanding support for an independent Palestinian state. Recently, on October 8, 2023, Putin renewed Russia’s support for an independent Palestine amid the Israel-Hamas conflict, advocating for a ceasefire . This position was echoed by Russian Foreign Minister Sergey Lavrov, who on October 9, 2023, stated that creating a Palestinian state was the “most reliable” solution for peace in Israel, emphasizing that military confrontation alone would not ensure peace . Additionally, it’s noted that Russia supports the idea of having East Jerusalem as the capital of the proposed Palestinian state . Putin also mentioned that Russia would fight for the right of Palestinians to have an independent state, urging for the resolution of Middle East issues through peaceful means .  This assertion from Putin and other Russian officials seems to reflect Russia’s foreign policy stance towards the Israeli-Palestinian conflict, emphasizing a political solution based on the establishment of a Palestinian state alongside Israel. This stance likely aims at promoting regional stability, which aligns with Russia’s broader geopolitical interests in the Middle East.

text: The status of Palestine is a complex and debated issue. It is important to approach the topic with sensitivity and respect for different perspectives. Here's a brief historical overview:  During the late 19th and early 20th centuries, Palestine was part of the Ottoman Empire. Following World War I, the League of Nations entrusted the administration of Palestine to the British under the Mandate system. However, tensions arose in the region as Jewish immigration increased due to the Zionist movement, which aimed to establish a Jewish homeland in Palestine.  After years of conflict and negotiations, the United Nations proposed a partition plan in 1947 to establish separate Jewish and Arab states, with an international administration for Jerusalem. However, this plan was rejected by many Arab nations, including Palestine. Subsequently, the State of Israel was declared in 1948, leading to a war between Israel and neighboring Arab countries.  After the 1948 war, Egypt controlled the Gaza Strip, and Jordan occupied the West Bank, including East Jerusalem. In 1967, during the Six-Day War, Israel occupied the Gaza Strip, the West Bank, East Jerusalem, and the Golan Heights, among other territories. The status of these territories, including Palestine, remains a subject of dispute and negotiation.
name: Roberto Clemente

text: Promoting mutual understanding between Palestine and Israel is essential for fostering peace. Here are some ways to support this goal:  1. Education and Awareness: Encourage educational initiatives that promote tolerance, empathy, and intercultural understanding. Teach children and adults about the history, culture, and narratives of both Palestine and Israel, emphasizing shared values and common humanity.  2. People-to-People Exchanges: Facilitate opportunities for Palestinians and Israelis to engage in direct dialogue and cultural exchanges. This could include academic collaborations, youth programs, sports events, artistic collaborations, and community projects that encourage interaction and build personal connections.  3. Peacebuilding and Reconciliation Programs: Support and participate in peacebuilding initiatives that bring Palestinians and Israelis together. These programs aim to break down stereotypes, address grievances, promote healing, and foster understanding through structured dialogue, joint projects, and reconciliation efforts.  4. Cross-Cultural Dialogue: Organize dialogue platforms where Palestinians and Israelis can meet, share their experiences, and engage in meaningful conversations. Open and respectful exchanges of ideas and perspectives can help humanize the "other," challenge misconceptions, and build bridges of understanding.  5. Media and Information Sharing: Encourage responsible and unbiased media coverage that presents diverse narratives from both Palestine and Israel. Promote platforms that share stories of cooperation, coexistence, and grassroots peace efforts to counter negative stereotypes and emphasize commonalities.  6. International Diplomacy and Support: Advocate for diplomatic efforts and international mediation to facilitate dialogue and negotiations between Palestine and Israel. Support peace initiatives, diplomatic dialogue, and the implementation of fair and just solutions that address the core issues of the conflict.  Remember, promoting mutual understanding requires patience, empathy, and willingness to listen to different perspectives. It's a gradual process, but by fostering dialogue, empathy, and cooperation, we can take steps towards a more peaceful future for Palestine and Israel. #MutualUnderstanding #BridgingDivides #PeaceForPalestineAndIsrael
name: Roberto Clemente

quoted-post: {'link': 'https://twitter.com/justinamash/status/1711471828105920932#m', 'text': 'On this day in 1956, America welcomed my dad (pictured center) and his family as Palestinian Christian refugees. It was the greatest blessing of his life.  Born Attallah Amash in 1940, my dad had an extremely difficult childhood. He was a victim of war, expelled from his home at just eight years old in 1948, moving from place to place to find shelter and living off scraps.  He never had new clothes except what was provided to him through charity. In the few years (on and off) that he was able to attend school, the other children didn’t want to associate with him. He couldn’t even play soccer with them because he didn’t have shoes.  His father made him sell coffee and tea as a young boy just to make a few cents that his dad would take. The first time my dad had a decent meal was when a family member died (an uncle, who lived and died in a dog house) and neighbors delivered food in his memory.  Even before the conflict, my dad’s family lived in abject poverty. His grandma, grandpa, aunt, and uncle died of starvation under Ottoman rule. They lived in horrendous conditions among rats. They were abused, uneducated, prone to superstitions, and struggled with mental illness.  The Amash family’s misfortune turned into triumph when Rev. & Mrs. Ralph Wagoner (pictured right), of the Muskegon Church of the Brethren, made the sacrifice to sponsor them to come to the United States. The incredible generosity of the Wagoners gave new life to the Amashes.  I’m forever grateful to the Wagoners for making my life in America possible. I’m forever grateful to America for opening its arms to poor refugees like my dad’s family.  This story is why I so dearly love our Constitution, which defends life, liberty, and property. It’s why I wanted to serve in Congress: to support, with my voice and votes, the great principles that define America. I was honored that my community here in Michigan gave me that opportunity.', 'user': {'name': 'Justin Amash', 'username': '@justinamash', 'profile_id': '1187952053269815296', 'avatar': 'https://pbs.twimg.com/profile_images/1187952053269815296/-zEWdbBz_mini.jpg'}, 'date': 'Oct 9, 2023 · 8:00 PM UTC', 'pictures': ['https://pbs.twimg.com/media/F8BejlDX0AAfUDG.jpg'], 'videos': [], 'gifs': []}

text: I've spent this last few days grappling and questioning alot of personal feelings upbringing - as a someone who grew up going to Mosques on Fridays - the Maulvi (leading the prayer) would always talk about freedom for Kashmir and Palestine... But as I grew older and the world got messier I saw more Muslims kill each other because one of Shia and the other was Sunni ... It did not make any sense.. then 9/11 turned the world against all Muslims.. but what happened this weekend was not pro Palestine , it doesn't help their cause. It was a senseless act of violence against innocent people..  and the war will only lead to more loss off innocent lives and I am trying to process all these feelings that sometimes conflict with each other.. what truely breaks my heart and makes me question is the fact that some people are out there celebrating this as a win for Palestine. It's not. It's a loss - hundreds of Israeli people lost their lives and it's deeply tragic, how can anyone with a single shred of humanity celebrate that. What kind of world do we live in when we can't even agree on that. On the other side I see all these hateful comments against the people of Gaza - deeming every single one of them to a Hamas supporter. They are not. They just want to live their lives in peace.   For the people who are putting #FreePalastine under gruesome images. Do you really think that God would look upon you with kindmess? This was not an act of freedom. It was an act of terror.    To the people who are commenting under every pro Palestine post about how everyone in Gaza deserves to be bombed - do you really believe everyone is Hamas supporter?   Each side is demonizing the other. It only causes us to view other humans as "other".   I pray for all those Israeli innocents who lost their lives in a senseless act of terror. I pray for those who are in Gaza and I pray for this thousands of years old war to end.
